### Why This Structure

| Decision | Rationale |
|---|---|
| **`server/` as separate directory** (not a separate repo) | Monorepo keeps everything in one place; shared types possible; single `docker-compose` spins up everything |
| **Express over NestJS** | Lower ceremony, faster to ship, more idiomatic for a project this size. NestJS's DI + decorators add overhead without clear benefit here |
| **Raw `pg` with query files** instead of Drizzle | Drizzle adds a build step and migration tooling that complicates the setup. Raw SQL queries in typed functions are simpler, more transparent, and you control every query. If you prefer Drizzle, I can switch вЂ” see Q1 below |
| **`validators/` with Zod** | Strict runtime validation on Gemini responses + user input. Never trust `as SomeType` |
| **`services/` per integration** | Each provider has different auth, pagination, and data mapping. Separate files keep them testable and replaceable |
| **No `models/` directory** | With raw `pg`, there are no ORM model classes. Types live in `types/`, queries live in `db/queries/` |

