## Auth Flow Design

### Overview

Google OAuth 2.0 serves **dual purpose**: authenticates the user AND provides the OAuth token for Gmail + Calendar API access. This eliminates the need for users to manually paste a Google token.

### Flow Diagram

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as Browser
    participant FE as React SPA
    participant BE as Express Backend
    participant G as Google OAuth
    participant DB as PostgreSQL
    participant RD as Redis

    Note over U,RD: === Login Flow ===
    
    U->>FE: Click "Sign in with Google"
    FE->>BE: GET /auth/google
    BE->>U: 302 Redirect в†’ Google Consent Screen
    Note over G: Scopes requested:<br/>openid, profile, email,<br/>gmail.readonly, calendar.readonly
    U->>G: User grants consent
    G->>BE: GET /auth/google/callback?code=xxx
    
    BE->>G: Exchange code for tokens (server-side)
    G-->>BE: { access_token, refresh_token, id_token, expiry }
    
    BE->>DB: Upsert user (email, name, avatar from id_token)
    BE->>DB: Upsert integration (provider='google', encrypted tokens)
    BE->>RD: Create session { userId, email }
    BE->>U: Set-Cookie: sid=xxx (httpOnly, Secure, SameSite=Lax)<br/>302 Redirect в†’ /dashboard

    Note over U,RD: === Authenticated API Call ===
    
    FE->>BE: GET /api/inbox (Cookie: sid=xxx)
    BE->>RD: Validate session в†’ get userId
    BE->>DB: Get google integration for userId
    BE->>BE: Decrypt access_token
    BE->>G: Fetch Gmail + Calendar (Bearer token)
    G-->>BE: Email/Calendar data
    BE-->>FE: Normalized InboxItem[]
    
    Note over U,RD: === Token Refresh (Transparent) ===
    
    BE->>G: Gmail call fails (401)
    BE->>G: POST /token (refresh_token)
    G-->>BE: New access_token
    BE->>DB: Update encrypted access_token
    BE->>G: Retry Gmail call
    G-->>BE: Success
```

### Key Auth Decisions

| Decision | Choice | Why |
|---|---|---|
| **Session strategy** | Server-side sessions in Redis (via `express-session` + `connect-redis`) | More secure than JWT in cookies вЂ” sessions can be invalidated server-side instantly. Redis keeps session lookups fast |
| **Cookie settings** | `httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'lax', maxAge: 7 days` | `httpOnly` prevents XSS access. `lax` (not `strict`) because we need the cookie sent during the Google OAuth redirect back |
| **Token storage** | Encrypted in PostgreSQL (`integrations` table) | AES-256-GCM with a server-side `ENCRYPTION_KEY` from `.env`. Tokens never leave the server |
| **Token refresh** | Transparent server-side rotation | When a Google API call returns 401, the backend automatically refreshes using the stored refresh_token, updates the DB, and retries |
| **SameSite = Lax** | Not Strict | `SameSite=Strict` would block the cookie on the OAuth callback redirect from Google в†’ our backend. `Lax` allows top-level navigations (which is exactly what the OAuth redirect is) |

### OAuth Scopes Requested

```
openid                                    в†’ Get user identity (id_token)
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/userinfo.email    в†’ Email address
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/userinfo.profile  в†’ Name + avatar
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.readonly    в†’ Read Gmail
https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.readonly в†’ Read Calendar events
```

> [!NOTE]
> Requesting Gmail + Calendar scopes at login time means the user **never needs to manually configure Google integration** вЂ” it's automatic. Slack and Jira still require manual token input (P0), with proper OAuth flows deferred to P2.

